column1: How many total Fast Charge (>22kW) public charging points for electric vehicles will be installed in the European Union by 31 December 2022?
column5: [' Less than 25,000', 'Between 25,000 and 30,000, inclusive', 'More than 30,000 but less than 35,000', 'Between 35,000 and 40,000, inclusive', 'More than 40,000']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology', 'Environment']
All in.

Looking at the data for 2021YTD, looks to be up 5k to just below 30k already. Not clear what YTD actually means here, but even if it was up to the day, arithmetic would now get us to 40k and this seems much more likely to be a geometric process.
Too many car producers going electric to ignore the charging stations

A simple exponential brings us to >50k. Solar PV defied even exponential models and there is quite a high likelihood EVs will too. The only things that could slow down deployment of fast chargers would be either permitting processes which is a real concern and/or grid congestion (e.g. the acute shortage of electricity in Stockholm). That said, there are many countries in EU where there are comparatively very few charging outlets and these constraining factors will only be an issue in a few, select regions. Moreover, fast chargers are ususally located along high-ways and other infrastructure which both means the grid is less congested and permitting should be easier. I am inclined to actually revise to 100% but that feels perhaps a bit over confident but would be aligned with a >0.5% chance of ending up below 40k. I wished the question poser would have used evidence from cost declines in renewables to understand that she or he should have widened this range dramatically. I think there is a chance we will blow way past 50k and might end up perhaps somewhere near 70k. Chance of that? Perhaps 5%. Sad that this cannot be captured by the way the question is set up. Maybe I should pose the same question but with wider ranges?
No contest. An EV in every parking lot and a charger in every lot. Even dogs will be wearing charging collars. You will just plug them in, no more puppy chow.
I think the crowd is too conservative. I know - really unscientific. But I do not want to fall trap to the same issue pestering those who tried to forecast solar in the 2000's.
My bet is based more of a leap of faith than on analysis. European car companies are going all in for EVs; more chargers will be needed.
Not in EU; seems likely to continue to point X - with more planning. Post covid more ppl traveling -

Over the past five years the average annual growth rate is 50.4%. At this growth rate the number of total Fast Charge public charging points for electric vehicles will greatly exceed 40,000 by the end of 2022.
On pace to surpass, as well as in the interests of transportation of goods throughout the continent as they can rely upon shorter range trucks given the shorter routes required.

Being already over 25,000 (accounting for 2020), 40,000 is looking in reach. For example, if the same building rate in 2020 continues for 2021 and 2022 then 45,000 charging points will be reached. I expect some slow down, but two years to react to the increasing amounts of EVs being sold (https://europe.autonews.com/automakers/german-electric-car-sales-triple-2020, https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/dec/03/more-than-500000-full-electric-cars-sold-in-europe-in-10-months). My previous estimate that people wouldn't be interested in excessive amounts of available fast charging still exists, but >22kW isn't too powerful and there is enough interest from industry discussions. Certainly, I think the limiting factor [for this question] will now be the construction speeds and electricity networks, which should comfortably be able to tackle 40,000.
Updating given December numbers. Exponential process so big number more likely.

It then looks completely unreasonable we will be at <30k and even <35k by 2022. I am therefore updating my forecast towards the high end. 15k to 20k from 2019 to 2020. Rate of increase is non-linear. https://www.eafo.eu/alternative-fuels/electricity/charging-infra-stats# https://www.transportenvironment.org/sites/te/files/publications/01%202020%20Draft%20TE%20Infrastructure%20Report%20Final.pdf suggests approx doubling from 2020 to 2022. Suggest around 45k but impact of COVID on world economy could reduce this.

Fast charging is a useful tool, but there are arguments to say that it will not massively improve uptake of EV (the research in question referred to the US), leading to a few problems here. Firstly, fast charging is only likely to be of major use in densely populated areas which many cities in the EU are (https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S136192091930896X) However the move to EVs may require some form of government stimulus - both in terms of financials and confidence. What better way to show commitment to EV infrastructure than some fast charging units in a few cities. The number would quickly stack up. Government/industry priorities will probably be on home charging stations, but fast charging units will be attractive.
The reduction of CO² has to be driven forward but the Hydrogen answer cannot be realised by the end of 2022.

Skewed it a bit to the upside within that given it does feel like there should be a lot of upside to this sort of build out/process.

Stats updated [1] as of Oct 1st [2]. 21,384 through that period. Updating model [3] accordingly. Average of projected exponential and linear growth seems to be tracking most closely to actuals. Given that, I've done away with my asymmetric distribution and applied a normal distribution around my currently forecasted 35,813 by end of 2022. Likely error to be on high end, might revise to bump up as number could be closer to 46,344.

On target for around 22k end of 2020. Past years growth rate at around 40% and everything looks set to continue this trend, or increase further. I think a conservative 30-35% increase is realistic, giving a total that could tip above 40K.

Based on current total for 2020, the total 19,543, is running ahead of the lower bound projection I had for 2020 (19525), so even with COVID, fast charging stations are continuing to be installed in the EU [1].

Yearly growth rates according to https://www.eafo.eu/alternative-fuels/electricity/charging-infra-stats: 2014 96% 2015 130% 2016 53% 2017 68% 2018 27% 2019 35%. Geometric mean is 53% for the last 7 years, 42% for the last three and 31 for the last two years. Growth in 2020 has been 30% in 6 months, so around 70% per year.

Quadratic regression gives us around 32,000. Exponential regression gives us a lot higher than that, but I don't think it's as appropriate to use here. Not gonna lean heavily toward any one category here since the closing date is so far out.

Similar to @chiefthe 's forecast [1], I took a look at polynomial vs exponential growth. I've adjusted for different standard deviations up versus down which gives a non-normal distribution of probabilities.

Number of chargers for 2019 is 15k [1]. Doing a quick polynomial projection (2nd order) gives about 30k at the end of 2022 [2], which I'll use as a lower bound, as these would seem to benefit from the acceleration due to network effects. For an upper bound, I am assuming an exponential projection of the *total* number of all public charging stations from [1], with a fixed percentage of those (max % from the last few years) being fast-charging stations [2]. This gives an upper bound of 77k for 2022.

Current number of Fast Chargers in the EU is about 18K growing to perhaps 20K in 2020. That would be a rate of 5K chargers added per year. Assume the rate remains 5k Fast Chargers per year for 2021 and 2022. It would appear 30K Fast chargers end of 2022. With a conserted program more may be possible, but the EU will not be back to normal for quite a while and funds to support may not appear. Even 30K is a stretch goal in the current economic environment.
Will look at the numbers and reevaluate...
